The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Saturday, May 29, 2004 				 Year-end debut for cancer unit
 A STAFF REPORTER																								The state-of-the-art cancer treatment unit of the Advanced Medicare and Research Institute (AMRI) Hospitals will be operational by the end of this year. 																								The unit, with radiotherapy, medical and surgical oncology departments, will be a part of the new 180-bed hospital.																								The cancer treatment unit will be operational by the end of this year, while the other units are likely to be completed by the middle of next year, said S.B. Purakayastha, president, AMRI, on Friday. Cardiology, cardiac surgery, orthopaedics and trauma centres will form part of the new hospital, coming up adjacent to the old building.																								The hospital announced the opening of three specialised clinics on diabetes, asthma and allergy and chronic backache. 																								Other specialised clinics on chronic headache and menopause will be set up soon, Purakayastha said.																								A.K. Sinha, in charge of the diabetes clinic, said patients will be guided on how to control blood sugar and will be encouraged to go in for regular check-ups on their own. 																								Asthma patients will be treated on five visits to the clinic over a period of six months, said Subhasish Ghosh, who is heading the asthma and allergy clinic. 																								The clinic will provide an asthma pack for patients and draw a guideline to tackle asthma at home.
